    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="784"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d784">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.115 St 2/11</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spring Rice</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Ambassador presents his compliments to the Secretary of State of
                    the United States and has the honour to state that, according to information
                    which has reached His Majesty’s Government, two German oil steamships lying at
                    Baton Rouge, the <hi rend="italic">Chatham</hi> and <hi rend="italic"
                        >Standard</hi>, which belonged to the German-American Company of Hamburg,
                    have been sold to the Standard Oil Company of New Jersey and their names changed
                    to <hi rend="italic">Montano</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Caloria</hi>
                    respectively.</p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Ambassador is instructed to say that His Majesty’s Government
                    consider themselves entitled to seize these ships on the ground that the sale
                    was effected only in order to escape risk of capture.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>,</closer>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-17">
                        <hi rend="italic">October 17, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 19</hi>.] </dateline>
            </div>
        </body>
